{
  "id": "019cf625-7dd3-7a72-90bd-3573034d52a2",
  "content": "sys/class/drm/card*</span><br>\n    <span class=\"output\">card0 <span class=\"highlight-val\">NVIDIA</span> &rarr; HDMI-A-1, eDP-2</span><br>\n    <span class=\"output\">card1 <span class=\"highlight-val\">Intel</span>&nbsp; &rarr; DP-1, DP-2, eDP-1</span>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"card\" style=\"border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-amber); margin-bottom: 16px;\">\n    <div style=\"font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.7;\">\n      <strong>The problem:</strong> When I set apps to render on the iGPU but displayed\n      through HDMI (NVIDIA-wired), frames had to copy across GPUs via\n      <em>Reverse PRIME</em>. That caused <strong>stuttering</strong>.\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"card\" style=\"border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-green);\">\n    <div style=\"font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.7;\">\n      <strong>The fix:</strong> Swapped to USB-C (Intel-wired). Now the iGPU renders\n      <em>and</em> outputs directly &mdash; no frame copying. RTX 3060 dropped to <strong>0%</strong>.\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"insight-box\">\n    <p>Sometimes the best optimization is just <strong>changing a cable</strong>.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"flex-grow\"></div>\n  <div class=\"author-tag\">Lim Chun Zhe</div>\n  <div class=\"slide-number\">06 / 08</div>\n</div>\n\n<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->\n<!-- SLIDE 7: THE PROOF (SCREENSHOTS)                -->\n<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->\n<div class=\"slide\">\n  <div class=\"slide-label\">The Proof</div>\n  <div class=\"slide-title\">\n    RTX 3060 at <span class=\"highlight-green\">0%</span>.<br>\n    Intel iGPU <span class=\"highlight-cyan\">Handling It.</span>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"slide-subtitle\" style=\"font-size: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px;\">\n    Actual screenshot from my Ubuntu machine after the changes.\n  </div>",
